<BaseLayout title="Dog-Friendly Beaches Mornington Peninsula | Peninsula Insider" description="A practical Peninsula Insider guide to dog-friendly beaches on the Mornington Peninsula, including year-round off-leash options, restricted beaches, and what to avoid." section="explore" ogImage="/images/sourced/dog-beach-hero-01.webp">
  <main class="article-shell container prose" style="padding: 3rem 0 4rem; max-width: 820px;">
    <p class="label label--accent">Dog-Friendly Peninsula</p>
    <h1>Dog-Friendly Beaches on the Mornington Peninsula</h1>
    <p><img src="/images/sourced/dog-beach-hero-01.webp" alt="Dog running on a beach" style="width:100%; border-radius: 18px; margin: 0 0 1.5rem; object-fit: cover;" /></p>
    <p>The Peninsula is full of beach imagery, but not every beach is equally useful when the dog is part of the day. The right dog beach is not just pretty. It has workable access, enough space, clear rules, and a lower chance of turning the morning into a signage dispute or a parking headache.</p>
    <p>The first thing to know is this: dog rules changed across parts of the Mornington Peninsula in late 2024, and the Shire’s current beach controls should always outrank older travel posts. Treat the Shire map and beach signage as the final word before you go.</p>

    <h2>The strongest year-round off-leash beaches</h2>
    <p>If you want the cleanest dog-beach experiences, start here.</p>
    <ul>
      {yearRound.map((beach) => (
        <li><strong>{beach.name}</strong> ({beach.location}) — {beach.note}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <h2>The beaches that only work at certain times</h2>
    <p>These are the beaches people often mean when they say “dogs are allowed there”, but the detail matters. During daylight saving, many of these beaches move into restricted access windows and only work early or late. In winter, some are effectively more usable. That makes them planning beaches, not default beaches.</p>
    <ul>
      {restricted.map((beach) => <li>{beach}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>Where not to build your dog day</h2>
    <p>Some of the Peninsula’s most dramatic coastline is simply not for dogs. That is especially true across the national park coast. Do not rely on old “best dog beaches” blog posts that blur this line.</p>
    <ul>
      {avoid.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
    </ul>

    <h2>Best practical use cases</h2>
    <p><strong>For an easy dog-beach morning:</strong> Tassells Cove or Somers.</p>
    <p><strong>For a northern-side stay:</strong> Fosters Beach or Royal Beach.</p>
    <p><strong>For a Flinders day:</strong> Flinders Dog Beach, then coffee or a village stop.</p>

    <h2>What matters more than the postcard</h2>
    <p>For dog owners, the real quality test is simple: can the dog move, can the humans stay calm, and can the day keep working after the beach? Parking, rinse options, nearby walks, lunch plans, and the actual stress level matter more than the prettiest view.</p>
    <p>Use this page as the practical starting point, then double-check the current Mornington Peninsula Shire controls before locking in the plan.</p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
